article.description:
As Bonzi Wells sees it, the Detroit
Pistons gave up on the wrong man.
article.headline: Blazers send Pistons to seventh defeat in a row
article.linkText: Wells teaches Pistons a lesson with career-high 37
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- As Bonzi Wells sees it, the Detroit Pistons gave up on the wrong man. Wells was a first-round choice by Detroit back in 1998, but was shipped to Portland before he'd even played a game for the Pistons in exchange for a first-rounder in 1999. ''You definitely want to let a team know who gave up on you that you can play in this league,'' Wells said after scoring a career-high 37 points in the Trail Blazers' 103-86 rout of the Pistons on Sunday night. It was Detroit's seventh consecutive defeat. ''It feels good, especially against the team that drafted me and let me go,'' Wells said. Wells went on a tear in the third quarter, scoring 18 points to help the Blazers pull away and win their fourth in a row. His previous career high was 35, set last season at Minnesota. The Pistons finished their West Coast road trip 0-5. They haven't lost seven in a row since Dec. 16-28, 2001, a streak that also began with five consecutive defeats in the West. Portland led just 44-42 at halftime, but opened the third quarter with a 15-5 run. When Wells scored and was fouled on a fastbreak layup to put the Blazers ahead 59-47 with 7:36 left in the period, coach Maurice Cheeks pumped his fist on the sideline. The Blazers, who outscored the Pistons 34-18 in the quarter, led by as many as 27 points. ''They executed great the entire game, but the third quarter they played at a different level than we did,'' Detroit coach Rick Carlisle said. Wells brought the biggest cheer of the night when he hit a 3-pointer with 27 seconds left in the third to make it 78-58. Afterward, however, he appeared to tauntingly pat the knee of one of the Detroit coaches and was issued a technical foul. Chauncey Billups, coming off a season-high 33-point performance at Golden State on Saturday night, scored 21 to lead Detroit. ''We are a good basketball team, and the most important thing for us right now is to stay confident and stay positive,'' Billups said. ''We know we are the same team that came out the No. 1 team in the East.'' Rasheed Wallace, who missed the victory Friday night over the Los Angeles Clippers because of a sore left Achilles' tendon, added 13 points for Portland. The Blazers have won six in a row against the Pistons and nine of the last 10. ''It was a heck of a defensive game for us,'' Cheeks said. ''We rode our defense, especially in the third quarter, and they just played off Bonzi. We just stayed with him, got the ball in his hands as much as we could, and we fed off him.'' The Pistons led 24-18 in the first quarter, but Wallace answered with a 3-pointer to narrow the gap, and the Blazers managed to keep it close. Portland went up 30-28 on Zach Randolph's turnaround jumper but couldn't stretch their lead any further and the Pistons went back ahead with a pair of jumpers from Corliss Williamson. Both sides wrestled with the lead the rest of the half, with the Blazers taking the slight advantage into halftime. ''This is definitely the wrong time of the year for a losing streak like this, but it just tests your character,'' Billups said. ''How we bounce back from this is going to tell us how good we really are.'' Game notes
The last time the two teams met, the Blazers spoiled a five-game Detroit winning streak at home with an 85-74 victory at the Palace on Dec. 30. ... Damon Stoudamire, used sparingly off the bench for most of the season, played 21 minutes and scored four points.
